body:
This is an Enhancement Request. This wrong code:

```rust
fn foo1(a: [u32; 3]) -> [u32; 2] {
    &a[1 ..]
}

fn main() {}
```

With rustc (1.48.0-nightly 0d0f6b113 2020-09-03) gives:

```rust
error[E0308]: mismatched types
 --> ...\test.rs:4:5
  |
3 | fn foo1(a: [u32; 3]) -> [u32; 2] {
  |                         -------- expected `[u32; 2]` because of return type
4 |     &a[1 ..]
  |     ^^^^^^^^ expected array `[u32; 2]`, found `&[u32]`
```

To encourage the usage of arrays I suggest to add a note (similar to the one given for numbers) that suggests to use ".try_into().unwrap()" leading the programmer to write code like this:

```rust
use std::convert::TryInto;

fn foo(a: [u32; 3]) -> [u32; 2] {
    a[1 ..].try_into().unwrap()
}

fn main() {}
```

(There is also the possibility to write code as `<[u32; 2]>::try_from(&a[1 ..]).unwrap()` but I think this is less nice looking in this case).
